00:12:00,557 --> 00:12:04,363
put the level draining slide up, there was an audible moan that went through the class.

252
00:12:07,848 --> 00:12:09,671
Again, these are some quotes from.

253
00:12:11,488 --> 00:12:14,490
from some DND forums about draining levels.

254
00:12:15,211 --> 00:12:17,392
And you can read that, but I've highlighted

255
00:12:17,432 --> 00:12:18,433
some of the other stuff in there.

256
00:12:18,854 --> 00:12:21,816
On the bottom, there is little you can do in DND

257
00:12:21,836 --> 00:12:23,577
to viscerally terrify players,

258
00:12:23,637 --> 00:12:25,718
but for whatever reason, level draining does it.

259
00:12:27,460 --> 00:12:28,440
And a couple of more quotes.

260
00:12:29,861 --> 00:12:31,182
This is all from the same thread.

261
00:12:31,442 --> 00:12:33,424
All versions of DND have some form of raised dead,

262
00:12:33,484 --> 00:12:34,725
not all versions have restoration.

263
00:12:34,785 --> 00:12:36,946
Many players would rather die than lose 50% of their XP.

264
00:12:39,190 --> 00:12:41,472
which I have verified with my daughter, she agreed with that.

265
00:12:42,152 --> 00:12:44,834
Maybe this is a more emotional than sensible reaction,

266
00:12:44,874 --> 00:12:46,015
but many players feel that way.

267
00:12:46,035 --> 00:12:47,736
And my favorite quote of the whole thing on the bottom

268
00:12:47,756 --> 00:12:49,898
there, but what I've always liked about level drain

269
00:12:49,938 --> 00:12:51,679
is just how personal that loss can be,

270
00:12:51,819 --> 00:12:53,340
as if part of the character's life

271
00:12:53,781 --> 00:12:56,443
truly was just ripped away forever, lessening them for it.

272
00:12:58,344 --> 00:13:01,826
That's a real visceral emotional response to losing something.

273
00:13:02,067 --> 00:13:03,688
And people don't even really, like I said,

274
00:13:03,748 --> 00:13:06,170
have that effect a lot of times if their characters die.

275
00:13:07,837 --> 00:13:10,037
It's the ending of a story, it's in some service,

276
00:13:10,097 --> 00:13:13,258
but level draining has a different aspect to it.

277
00:13:14,098 --> 00:13:16,099
And interestingly, if you look at D&D

278
00:13:16,139 --> 00:13:17,879
and what they've done over the years with level draining,

279
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:19,260
in Advanced Dungeons and Dragons,

280
00:13:19,480 --> 00:13:20,880
which is the first version I got into,

281
00:13:21,000 --> 00:13:22,721
level draining was there, it was an undead ability,

282
00:13:23,741 --> 00:13:25,402
and there was no save against level draining.

283
00:13:25,822 --> 00:13:27,642
You got hit by a white or a lich or something,

284
00:13:28,122 --> 00:13:28,643
you were screwed.

285
00:13:30,183 --> 00:13:31,183
In the third edition,

286
00:13:32,224 --> 00:13:33,644
there was a saving roll that was allowed.

287
00:13:34,935 --> 00:13:37,637
at least, but if it failed, you lost the level.

288
00:13:37,997 --> 00:13:39,579
Then in fourth edition, they completely

289
00:13:39,619 --> 00:13:40,500
got rid of level draining.

290
00:13:41,821 --> 00:13:43,742
And if you go to Pathfinder, which

291
00:13:43,803 --> 00:13:45,904
is kind of like sort of an offshoot of third edition,

292
00:13:47,005 --> 00:13:50,088
they didn't make that many changes from third edition D&D,

293
00:13:50,108 --> 00:13:51,369
but one of the ones that they did was they

294
00:13:51,409 --> 00:13:52,250
got rid of level draining.

295
00:13:53,391 --> 00:13:54,912
So it's obviously that over the years

296
00:13:54,952 --> 00:13:57,074
that this was recognized as something that was not

297
00:13:57,134 --> 00:13:58,495
something that players wanted that

298
00:13:58,535 --> 00:14:01,198
put them into an emotional state that they found uncomfortable.

299
00:14:06,046 --> 00:14:08,748
So giving something to a player and then taking it away

300
00:14:10,229 --> 00:14:11,009
is really emotional.

301
00:14:11,409 --> 00:14:13,531
And that goes back to that idea of,

302
00:14:15,472 --> 00:14:18,794
from Risk Legacy, of forcing the players

303
00:14:18,834 --> 00:14:20,555
to tear up a card in the very beginning.

304
00:14:21,075 --> 00:14:24,297
Better not to have given them that card in the first place,

305
00:14:24,397 --> 00:14:25,878
or just have them randomly draw one

306
00:14:25,898 --> 00:14:27,039
and leave the other one in the box.

307
00:14:27,079 --> 00:14:28,800
You know, it has the same effect

308
00:14:29,901 --> 00:14:31,202
from a mechanical standpoint,

309
00:14:31,422 --> 00:14:32,623
but it does not have the same effect

310
00:14:32,643 --> 00:14:33,763
from an emotional standpoint.

311
00:14:38,369 --> 00:14:42,431
I'd like to take a quick detour into a game show

312
00:14:42,491 --> 00:14:44,872
that my family, including my in-laws,

313
00:14:44,912 --> 00:14:46,072
will no longer watch with me.

314
00:14:48,093 --> 00:14:48,933
Deal or no deal?

315
00:14:50,394 --> 00:14:52,315
I'm assuming most of you are familiar with the show.

316
00:14:52,395 --> 00:14:53,575
But for those of you that are not,

317
00:14:54,756 --> 00:14:59,258
there's a bunch of suitcases that all have varying values

318
00:14:59,278 --> 00:15:01,658
of money in them, ranging from $1 to $1 million.

319
00:15:01,699 --> 00:15:04,039
You pick one case at random that you're going to keep.

320
00:15:04,119 --> 00:15:05,700
And then you gradually open the cases,

321
00:15:05,940 --> 00:15:07,621
showing the money so you know what you didn't get.

322
00:15:08,459 --> 00:15:10,079
and then at various points in the game,

323
00:15:10,480 --> 00:15:13,180
there's a banker that comes on, very shadowy figure,

324
00:15:13,340 --> 00:15:15,441
and he offers you money for your case.

325
00:15:16,581 --> 00:15:20,562
Now, from a purely mathematical standpoint,

326
00:15:21,622 --> 00:15:23,862
there's, you know, you know the expectation value

327
00:15:23,882 --> 00:15:25,343
of that case, you know the average value

328
00:15:25,363 --> 00:15:26,403
of all the cases that are left,

329
00:15:26,763 --> 00:15:29,124
and the expectation value that remains is, you know,

330
00:15:29,164 --> 00:15:31,724
the average of that is what you should get for it.

331
00:15:31,784 --> 00:15:33,845
If it's less than that, you're leaving money on the table.

332
00:15:35,401 --> 00:15:39,903
But the reality is in the show is that the banker always offers less than the expectation value.

333
00:15:40,003 --> 00:15:45,166
It's actually really interesting if you track the show is the first round they offer way, way less than the expectation value

334
00:15:45,566 --> 00:15:46,666
and they gradually approach it.

335
00:15:47,387 --> 00:15:50,268
It's just they don't want people walking away in the beginning of the game.

336
00:15:51,489 --> 00:15:56,771
But why does anybody take the offer if they're leaving that money on the table?

337
00:15:58,212 --> 00:16:02,594
And this goes back to the first one of the first examples that we did, which is

338
00:16:04,107 --> 00:16:06,788
captured in a psychological theory called utility theory.

339
00:16:08,708 --> 00:16:11,209
And that goes to the idea that if I'm offering you

340
00:16:11,229 --> 00:16:13,150
a million dollars or two million dollars,

341
00:16:13,950 --> 00:16:16,792
as far as you're concerned, it's probably not gonna,

342
00:16:17,052 --> 00:16:19,012
getting the two million dollars is not gonna change your life

343
00:16:19,373 --> 00:16:21,974
as much as getting that first million dollars is gonna be.

344
00:16:22,494 --> 00:16:24,915
So in your mind, they're about the same amount of money.

345
00:16:26,925 --> 00:16:29,207
And that's really what Deal or No Deal is playing on,

346
00:16:29,247 --> 00:16:30,868
is it's playing on people's, okay,

347
00:16:31,368 --> 00:16:33,110
this, you know, the guy's offering me $120,000,

348
00:16:33,150 --> 00:16:36,132
but it could be a million dollars.

349
00:16:37,033 --> 00:16:38,153
So for me personally,

350
00:16:38,294 --> 00:16:40,175
where is that falling on my utility spectrum?

351
00:16:40,655 --> 00:16:41,916
And that's what's interesting to watch.

352
00:16:41,976 --> 00:16:43,618
It's interesting to watch people struggle

353
00:16:43,658 --> 00:16:47,240
with that idea of, you know, it's not just the number,

354
00:16:47,321 --> 00:16:48,802
it's not just going for the biggest number,

355
00:16:49,442 --> 00:16:50,323
but it's the utility

356
00:16:50,363 --> 00:16:51,664
and how that's gonna apply to your life.

357
00:16:52,751 --> 00:16:55,471
Now if we go back to that first example that I gave you guys

358
00:16:55,792 --> 00:16:56,452
about the chance to get $3,000

359
00:16:56,912 --> 00:16:58,452
and the 80% chance to get $4,000,

360
00:16:58,752 --> 00:17:03,773
our brains are not great at math for the most part.

361
00:17:04,713 --> 00:17:06,054
Most people see $3,000 and $4,000

362
00:17:06,794 --> 00:17:09,154
and put them in the same box in their brain.

363
00:17:10,394 --> 00:17:15,055
So really, for most people from a utility theory standpoint,

364
00:17:15,255 --> 00:17:18,476
this problem is really, I'm guaranteed to get X

365
00:17:18,816 --> 00:17:19,736
or I have an 80% chance to get X.

366
00:17:21,229 --> 00:17:23,050
And in that case, I'm always gonna take

367
00:17:23,090 --> 00:17:24,352
the one that's guaranteed to get X.

368
00:17:24,392 --> 00:17:26,995
The fact that it's $3,200 doesn't really apply

369
00:17:27,655 --> 00:17:29,237
that the expectation value is higher.

370
00:17:31,699 --> 00:17:35,684
So that's just another way of looking at these things,

371
00:17:35,704 --> 00:17:39,888
and we'll talk in a bit about bigger numbers as well.

372
00:17:42,791 --> 00:17:42,991
Okay.

373
00:17:46,703 --> 00:17:49,804
This example is, for those of you that are here,

374
00:17:49,864 --> 00:17:51,505
again, for the pandemic legacy talk.

375
00:17:52,805 --> 00:17:55,126
This is actually, it was a real study that was done

376
00:17:55,246 --> 00:17:57,226
that I did not choose because I did not know

377
00:17:57,246 --> 00:17:59,667
that I was gonna be directly after the pandemic legacy talk.

378
00:17:59,807 --> 00:18:01,167
But this is the problem.

379
00:18:01,627 --> 00:18:03,208
A deadly disease is rapidly spreading.

380
00:18:04,288 --> 00:18:06,228
If nothing is done, then 600 people will die.

381
00:18:09,249 --> 00:18:11,830
So a cure has been developed.

382
00:18:13,713 --> 00:18:16,074
But you have two choices of which cure you're going to do.

383
00:18:16,114 --> 00:18:19,777
You can either do choice A, remember 600 people

384
00:18:20,618 --> 00:18:21,758
will die if nothing is done.

385
00:18:21,938 --> 00:18:23,920
So choice A is that 200 people will be saved.

386
00:18:25,161 --> 00:18:29,744
And choice B is a 1 3rd chance that all 600 will be saved

387
00:18:29,804 --> 00:18:32,165
and a 2 3rd chance that nobody will be saved.

388
00:18:33,866 --> 00:18:35,487
So how many people here would do choice A?

389
00:18:37,649 --> 00:18:38,549
And how many would do B?

390
00:18:40,431 --> 00:18:40,671
Okay.

391
00:18:42,537 --> 00:18:45,958
When surveyed, about three quarters of people will do A.

392
00:18:46,158 --> 00:18:46,938
200 people will be saved.

393
00:18:50,039 --> 00:18:50,919
Let's do another problem.

394
00:18:51,659 --> 00:18:52,379
Same situation.

395
00:18:52,579 --> 00:18:53,960
Deadly disease is rapidly spreading.

396
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:55,640
If nothing is done, 600 people will die.

397
00:18:58,041 --> 00:19:00,702
In this case, you could take choice C,

398
00:19:01,162 --> 00:19:01,782
400 people will die.

399
00:19:04,003 --> 00:19:05,123
Or if you pick cure D,

400
00:19:05,483 --> 00:19:07,223
then there's a one-third chance that nobody dies,

401
00:19:07,524 --> 00:19:09,384
but a two-thirds chance that 600 people die.

402
00:19:10,644 --> 00:19:11,205
So who will take C?

403
00:19:13,657 --> 00:19:14,418
A lot fewer people.

404
00:19:14,718 --> 00:19:15,398
And who would take D?

405
00:19:17,519 --> 00:19:17,799
Okay.

406
00:19:19,660 --> 00:19:22,822
So, in this case 78% choose D.

407
00:19:23,422 --> 00:19:24,583
So most people are with you guys.

408
00:19:26,744 --> 00:19:28,525
So these are the four choices put together here.

409
00:19:29,405 --> 00:19:31,386
So, choice A, B, C, and D.

410
00:19:34,127 --> 00:19:35,668
Now since 600 people are gonna die,

411
00:19:35,908 --> 00:19:38,289
choice A and choice C, 200 people will be saved

412
00:19:38,309 --> 00:19:40,170
and 400 people will die, are exactly the same.

413
00:19:41,271 --> 00:19:44,314
And choice B and choice D are also exactly the same.

414
00:19:45,735 --> 00:19:49,338
So did anybody here pick A for the first one

415
00:19:49,378 --> 00:19:50,219
and D for the second one?

416
00:19:52,601 --> 00:19:53,302
That's very common.

417
00:19:54,042 --> 00:19:54,843
A lot of people do that.

418
00:19:56,304 --> 00:19:58,606
And this leads to a concept that's called framing.

419
00:19:59,627 --> 00:20:00,948
What is a gain or what is a loss?

420
00:20:02,590 --> 00:20:04,972
And this is another great manipulation tool

421
00:20:05,032 --> 00:20:06,073
for player psychology.

422
00:20:10,093 --> 00:20:12,075
If you say 200 people will be saved,

423
00:20:12,255 --> 00:20:15,416
that's a positive emotion.

424
00:20:15,857 --> 00:20:18,158
People like that, 200 people will be saved.

425
00:20:18,298 --> 00:20:19,619
And the other one is all probabilities.

426
00:20:20,059 --> 00:20:22,260
The other one is 400 people will die.

427
00:20:23,701 --> 00:20:25,842
So again, we're going back to that idea

428
00:20:25,882 --> 00:20:28,324
that people will take a gain,

429
00:20:28,644 --> 00:20:31,065
a sure gain over gambling to gain more.

430
00:20:31,645 --> 00:20:34,707
But people will gamble to avoid a sure loss.

431
00:20:35,198 --> 00:20:36,639
And that's exactly what's happening here.

432
00:20:37,059 --> 00:20:41,000
Except in this case, the outcomes are exactly the same.

433
00:20:41,060 --> 00:20:43,301
It's not, you know, losing money versus gaining money.

434
00:20:43,942 --> 00:20:45,862
But if you express it as saving people

435
00:20:46,003 --> 00:20:47,443
or express it as people dying,

436
00:20:47,863 --> 00:20:49,104
then people will approach it differently

437
00:20:49,144 --> 00:20:51,965
and will have a different response to it.

438
00:20:54,906 --> 00:20:56,667
So in a board game context,

439
00:20:59,428 --> 00:21:00,789
this can be used a lot of different ways.

440
00:21:01,927 --> 00:21:06,009
One of my new games which is coming out in the spring is called pick crew and

441
00:21:06,189 --> 00:21:11,512
it's about the players. It's a team based game where each team is trying to

442
00:21:11,953 --> 00:21:14,954
repair their race car and get it back out onto the track as quickly as possible

443
00:21:15,355 --> 00:21:19,337
against the other teams. If you make mistakes, it's a real time game. You're

444
00:21:19,357 --> 00:21:23,139
trying to do things as fast as possible. If you make mistakes, you get penalty

445
00:21:23,179 --> 00:21:23,379
points.

446
00:21:25,925 --> 00:21:27,686
And we looked at a couple different ways to do this.

447
00:21:27,746 --> 00:21:30,226
Originally, the way that we did it is you got points

448
00:21:30,766 --> 00:21:33,127
for doing good things, and if you got penalty points,

449
00:21:33,167 --> 00:21:33,807
you lost points.

450
00:21:36,087 --> 00:21:39,508
And we found that when this is aimed at families,

451
00:21:39,848 --> 00:21:43,248
and in a family game is, if you had a lot of kids playing

452
00:21:43,288 --> 00:21:45,469
and stuff like that, they didn't like losing the points

453
00:21:45,909 --> 00:21:47,149
if they made mistakes on the car.

454
00:21:47,189 --> 00:21:49,529
There's also a strategy to intentionally make mistakes

455
00:21:49,569 --> 00:21:51,450
to get back, you know, get your car out faster

456
00:21:51,490 --> 00:21:53,810
because the first team that's out can get a bonus

457
00:21:53,850 --> 00:21:54,730
and can earn extra things.

458
00:21:55,653 --> 00:21:57,913
So what we did instead, when we kind of saw that,

459
00:21:58,013 --> 00:21:59,374
is we flipped it around and we said,

460
00:21:59,434 --> 00:22:03,155
okay, if you get a penalty, you don't lose points,

461
00:22:03,195 --> 00:22:04,655
but all the other teams gain points.

462
00:22:07,416 --> 00:22:09,076
And it was easy because it was a score track

463
00:22:09,116 --> 00:22:11,157
and people just could move their tokens up on the track.

464
00:22:11,657 --> 00:22:12,877
And that worked really, really well.

465
00:22:13,077 --> 00:22:14,018
People enjoyed that.

466
00:22:16,078 --> 00:22:17,999
It opened it up, it took away the negative feelings.

467
00:22:18,159 --> 00:22:20,399
Okay, penalty points, I'm on there, it's fine.

468
00:22:20,899 --> 00:22:23,060
It also fortuitously enabled us

469
00:22:23,100 --> 00:22:24,720
to make the score track look like a racetrack.

470
00:22:25,411 --> 00:22:27,072
So you have a little car running around the racetrack.

471
00:22:27,312 --> 00:22:30,373
And just metaphorically, race cars don't usually go backwards.

472
00:22:31,413 --> 00:22:32,734
So you push the other cars forward.

473
00:22:33,114 --> 00:22:35,355
But it really just changed the whole dynamic of the game

474
00:22:35,375 --> 00:22:37,075
and the way that people approach the penalty points,

475
00:22:37,135 --> 00:22:40,257
that it helped your opponents instead of hurting you.

476
00:22:41,937 --> 00:22:45,038
I mentioned the Expanse game that's coming out.

477
00:22:45,518 --> 00:22:47,599
In that, there is a mechanic where you

478
00:22:49,424 --> 00:22:50,404
can keep an event.

479
00:22:51,285 --> 00:22:53,225
There's event cards, and you can save one for later.

480
00:22:53,245 --> 00:22:54,586
But if you choose to save one for later,

481
00:22:54,726 --> 00:22:55,806
it costs you a victory point.

482
00:22:56,226 --> 00:22:57,467
Or there's other things you can do in the game

483
00:22:57,487 --> 00:22:58,407
that cost you victory points.

484
00:22:59,307 --> 00:23:01,728
And I considered applying the same kind of idea

485
00:23:01,768 --> 00:23:03,408
that instead of costing you victory points,

486
00:23:03,468 --> 00:23:05,129
it could give bonuses to all the other players.

487
00:23:05,169 --> 00:23:06,749
But in that case, emotionally,

488
00:23:06,809 --> 00:23:08,410
I wanted the players to feel invested

489
00:23:08,430 --> 00:23:10,350
that they were really committing something

490
00:23:10,410 --> 00:23:13,271
into getting this event and saving it.

491
00:23:13,871 --> 00:23:15,352
So in that case, we chose to

492
00:23:16,473 --> 00:23:20,795
have it apply as a specific penalty to players where you actually have to give up victory

493
00:23:20,855 --> 00:23:22,755
points in order to do this action.

494
00:23:26,456 --> 00:23:30,317
In general, we have seen a shifting away from losses and players losing things over the

495
00:23:30,337 --> 00:23:30,497
years.

496
00:23:30,537 --> 00:23:35,178
I mean, the old school games, you know, from the, that we all grew up with, Monopoly and

497
00:23:35,259 --> 00:23:40,560
Risk, are very much about loss, but they're very much about a specific type of loss where

498
00:23:40,600 --> 00:23:41,780
you gain and then you lose.

499
00:23:42,553 --> 00:23:45,294
Okay, so in monopoly you start with no properties

500
00:23:46,035 --> 00:23:49,456
and money, you get properties and you get hopefully a little more money and then

501
00:23:49,916 --> 00:23:52,318
for everybody except for the winner you lose everything.

502
00:23:52,858 --> 00:23:57,360
Same thing for risk. Risk, you start with territories and you'll take more

503
00:23:57,440 --> 00:23:59,841
territories, you build up an empire and then it's taken away.

